<SubSection title="Tipping vs. Slipping" id="tip_slip">

Consider a box of length <i>l</i> that is sitting on a rough surface with an applied load <i>P</i> on the right side. 

As <i>P</i> increases, there are two possible scenarios: either the box will "slip" and start sliding along the surface, or the box will tip onto the right corner.  

<Image src='/Statics/FrictionFigures/TipSlip.jpg' width='5'>tipping vs. slipping</Image>

<p>
If the box experiences <b>slipping</b>, the normal force will act at a location can be written as  <DisplayEquation equation="\N = \\mu P" />. You can solve for the force <i>P</i> required for the box to slip. 

If the box experiences <b>tipping</b>, the normal force will act at the bottom right corner of the box, and the couple from the frictional force and <i>N</i> will create a moment causing the box to tip. 

To determine which of these scenarios will occur, you should write the equations of equilibrium for each case and solve for the force <i>P</i> required to cause either slipping or tipping. Whichever condition has the smallest force <i>P</i> will be the condition that occurs. 
</p>

<p>
<em>Note:</em> See below for an explanation of why the normal force does not act at the center of mass of the box.
</p>
<!-- From Lecture 27 -->

     <Example title="Location of normal force">

	<Image src='/Statics/FrictionFigures/NLocation.jpg' width='5'></Image>

        <p>
          If the normal force <i>N</i> acted at the middle of the box (at the center of mass), we would write the three equations of equilibrium as follows: 
	</p>
          <DisplayEquation equation="\\sum F_x = P - F_f = 0" />
	  <DisplayEquation equation="\\sum F_y = N - W = 0" />
	
	<p>
          So far, so good! However, we run into a problem when we write the sum of moments equation:  
	</p>

	  <DisplayEquation equation="\\\sum M_O = -Py = 0" />

	<p>
	The sum of moments equation about point O results in an expression that is not possible: we know that <i>P</> cannot be zero, so there must be some sort of moment about the center of the box from the normal force acting offset from the center of mass of the box. 

        </p>

      </Example>


